version that supports layers), You could make a layer underneath all your drawing/colour layers etc, and a layer above them. Use the airbrush on the layer underneath (low opacity, say, about 5% if you're working with a mouse. feel free to experiment and find what's comfortable) the drawing to create a glow around the edges using the dominant colour of the wings. On the layer above, airbrush lightly over the edges to bring the glow in, 'wrapping' it around the edges of the wings. You could probably even take the blur tool to the edges of the wing layers, too... but I'm not sure if that's really necessary.<br>
<br>
I think this works best with light coloured wings, dark colours don't exactly 'glow' like that in reality.<br>
<br>
Anyway, I hope that works for you<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p>'I like people who acknowledge that they're human without confirming that they're stupid'</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ubrolly711.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Brolly711</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(5/28/02 6:18:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3664.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How would I make it bright?</span><hr size=1> My original thought was to make a new layer above the picture and airbrush over the edges.. then I added a glossary blur and lower the layer opacity to make it blend more with the back ground. The effect looked amazing and it seemed to be missing something. That why I was wondering if anyone knew the exact process of the effect. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ulinabo.showPublicProfile?language=EN>LinaBo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>PK Angel</span><br> <font color=#336699>(5/28/02 6:43:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3664.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.marua.com/ifk/avatars/Linapic.jpg width=100 height=78></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How would I make it bright?</span><hr size=1> oh well, experiment<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  alot of things can be done in many different ways, the best usually being up to your preference<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p>'I like people who acknowledge that they're human without confirming that they're stupid'</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ubrianbork.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Brian Bork</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(5/28/02 8:54:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3664.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How would I make it bright?</span><hr size=1> I have a Photoshop book that helps with this very topic:<br>
<br>
It sort of requires you to flatten your image otherwise it's a bit harder to do the following:<br>
<br>
1. Duplicate the image layer.<br>
2. Use the Gaussian blur filter to blur the duplicate layer.<br>
3. Adjustments:<br>
- to reduce haze use the &quot;normal&quot; setting inconjunction with the opacity slider.<br>
- [this would be the effect you're going for] to soften it, choose &quot;Lighten&quot; in conjuction with the opacity slider.<br>
<br>
Here's how it comes out when applied:<br>
<br>
The first image: <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://members.tripod.com/ginzuishou/example.jpg">members.tripod.com/ginzuishou/example.jpg</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
The image with the above applied using the &quot;Lighten&quot; option.<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://members.tripod.com/ginzuishou/example_blur1.jpg">members.tripod.com/ginzuishou/example_blur1.jpg</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
I then used the eraser to erase areas of the blurred layer except for his skin.<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://members.tripod.com/ginzuishou/example_blur2.jpg">members.tripod.com/ginzuishou/example_blur2.jpg</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
The opacity for the blurred layer was set to 65% for the above examples.<br>
<br>
